<methodology slug="business-model-planning">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>market-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Four linked frameworks for niche viability scoring, Blue Ocean analysis, Value Proposition Canvas, and pricing model selection. Score 3-5 niches in parallel for comparative ranking.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>business-model</tag>
      <tag>niche-viability</tag>
      <tag>pricing-strategy</tag>
      <tag>value-proposition</tag>
      <tag>blue-ocean</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Business Model Planning</title>
    <summary>Business model planning covers four linked frameworks for evaluating whether a niche is worth pursuing and how to monetize it: niche-viability scoring (5-criteria weighted), Blue Ocean / Four Actions (market space creation), Value Proposition Canvas (pain-gain fit), and pricing-model selection. The core rule: score 3-5 niches in parallel — the framework's value is comparative ranking across niches, not an absolute go/no-go on a single one.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Entrepreneurs enter crowded niches based on gut feel or build products without a viable revenue model. Subjective niche scores feel imprecise without a structured rubric. Blue Ocean analysis on a single case suffers from survivorship bias. LLMs default to "tiered subscription" pricing regardless of the product economics. Parallel scoring with citation-required inputs and explicit model rejection reasons disciplines these failure modes.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-spec phase of a new product where TAM/SAM/SOM exists but no model decision yet</item>
        <item>Niche short-list that needs ranking before writing a spec.md</item>
        <item>Re-pricing an existing SaaS after churn spikes or competitor shift</item>
        <item>Pivoting into an adjacency — must justify which factors to eliminate or raise</item>
        <item>Founder needs a number ("is this niche worth pursuing?"), not an opinion</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure market sizing — use market-research-tam-sam-som first; pipe its output here</item>
        <item>Competitor feature/pricing scrape — use competitor-analysis first</item>
        <item>Already-priced product with PMF — use conversion-optimizer, not a canvas</item>
        <item>B2C consumer apps with ad-only revenue — pricing-research framework assumes paid value capture</item>
        <item>Internal tools, hobby projects, or commissioned client work with fixed scope/budget</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="niche-viability-scoring">
      <rule>
        <statement>Score 3-5 niches in parallel, never one in isolation. The framework produces a comparative ranking; its value is relative, not absolute.</statement>
        <rationale>A single niche score of 7.3 is meaningless without a comparison set. Scoring in isolation produces a number that confirms existing bias rather than forcing a real trade-off decision.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="five-criteria">
        <list>
          <item>Market Size (25%): score 1-10 where 1-3 = below $10M, 4-6 = $10-100M, 7-10 = above $100M SAM</item>
          <item>Competition (20%): score 1-10 where 1-3 = red ocean (10+ direct competitors), 4-6 = moderate (3-10), 7-10 = blue ocean (fewer than 3)</item>
          <item>Barriers to Entry (20%): score 1-10 where 1-3 = high barriers (capital, regulatory, patents), 4-6 = medium (technical expertise), 7-10 = low (execution only)</item>
          <item>Profitability (20%): score 1-10 where 1-3 = thin margins below 20%, 4-6 = OK margins 20-40%, 7-10 = high margins above 40%</item>
          <item>Your Fit (15%): score 1-10 where 1-3 = no relevant skills or audience, 4-6 = some transferable skills, 7-10 = deep expertise and existing audience</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>Cite a source URL for each criterion score. A score without a link is noise an agent can fabricate.</statement>
          <rationale>Unanchored scores shift with the analyst's mood across sessions; URL-backed scores are reproducible and challengeable.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="decision-thresholds">
        <list>
          <item>7.5-10: Strong opportunity — proceed</item>
          <item>5.5-7.4: Proceed with caution — identify the weakest criterion and mitigate</item>
          <item>3.5-5.4: Significant risks — require additional validation before committing</item>
          <item>below 3.5: Pass — do not enter this niche</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="weight-adjustment-warning">
        <rule testable="false">
          <statement>Keep criteria weights under version control. If weights are adjusted mid-comparison, restart the entire batch from scratch.</statement>
          <rationale>Changing weights after some niches are scored invalidates cross-niche comparisons; partial weight changes produce scores that cannot be compared against each other.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <note>The 25/20/20/20/15 weights were tuned for indie SaaS. Enterprise sales, hardware, and marketplace models need different weightings — document the change before scoring.</note>
      </section>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[## Niche: AI Writing Tool

| Criterion    | Score | Weight | Weighted | Source                        |
|-------------|-------|--------|----------|-------------------------------|
| Market Size  |   8   |  25%   |   2.00   | statista.com/ai-writing-2025  |
| Competition  |   4   |  20%   |   0.80   | g2.com/categories/ai-writing  |
| Barriers     |   6   |  20%   |   1.20   | openai.com/pricing            |
| Profitability|   7   |  20%   |   1.40   | baremetrics.com/open          |
| Your Fit     |   8   |  15%   |   1.20   | own assessment, ML background |
| **Total**    |       |        | **6.60** |                               |

Decision: PROCEED WITH CAUTION — differentiation required vs. crowded field
Risk: Competition score 4; mitigation: narrow to [specific vertical]]]></code>
        <note>One score at 4 (below 5) and one at 8 (above 7) — avoids default scoring of 6/7 for everything.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="blue-ocean-four-actions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run Four Actions only after a competitor-analysis document exists. Without a baseline of what competitors currently offer, "eliminate" has no meaning.</statement>
        <rationale>Blue Ocean analysis without competitive data produces aspirational fiction. The Strategy Canvas requires actual competitor offerings plotted on the Y-axis before the new curve can be drawn.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="four-actions">
        <list>
          <item>Eliminate: which factors the industry takes for granted should be removed entirely? (typically costly or assumed-required features users rarely value)</item>
          <item>Reduce: which factors should be reduced well below the industry standard? (over-engineered for actual user needs)</item>
          <item>Raise: which factors should be raised above the industry standard? (currently underserved relative to what buyers actually want)</item>
          <item>Create: which factors should be created that the industry has never offered? (generates new demand or new buyer population)</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="strategy-canvas">
        <p>Plot the X-axis as key competing factors (price, features, support, onboarding, integrations, etc.) and the Y-axis as level offered (low to high). Plot 3+ real competitors from the competitor-analysis JSON before drawing the new value curve. Require 3 real data points minimum; curves drawn without data are marketing.</p>
        <rule>
          <statement>Force the Strategy Canvas to plot against at least 3 real competitor data points pulled from competitive-analysis output. LLM-drawn curves default to showing the "winning case" without real competition plotted.</statement>
          <rationale>Survivorship bias: agents produce a strategy canvas that looks like the case study (Cirque, Yellow Tail) without actually plotting competitor offerings. The resulting curve is aspirational, not analytical.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="survivorship-bias-warning">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Citing Cirque du Soleil, Yellow Tail wine, Nintendo Wii, or iTunes as Blue Ocean examples</description>
          <reason>These are the 5-7 textbook cases cited because they succeeded. The failure rate of "create new factor" bets is high and invisible. Require post-2018 examples and reject the canonical textbook cases.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Running Blue Ocean analysis on a single niche without a comparison set</description>
          <reason>Blue Ocean is only meaningful when contrasted against a current red ocean; without it you cannot identify what to eliminate or reduce.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="value-proposition-canvas">
      <section name="customer-profile">
        <list>
          <item>Customer Jobs: functional (tasks to complete), emotional (feelings sought), social (how they want to appear to others)</item>
          <item>Pains: obstacles, frustrations, and risks that block job completion — ranked by intensity</item>
          <item>Gains: desired outcomes and benefits — ranked by relevance (essential, expected, desired, unexpected)</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>Cap at most 2 pains above 7/10 per persona. If more than 2 pains exceed 7/10, the agent has inflated the scores.</statement>
          <rationale>Pain inflation makes every problem look existential; it eliminates the prioritization signal that the canvas is supposed to produce.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Bind pains to interview transcript IDs from user-interviews-methods. Uncited pains decay fastest and are the first to be invalidated by market changes.</statement>
          <rationale>VPC pains shift quarterly in early markets; a 6-month-old canvas without transcript anchors is fiction. Citation enables targeted re-validation of specific pain items.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="value-map">
        <list>
          <item>Products and Services: what is offered (feature list, not the benefit)</item>
          <item>Pain Relievers: how each product/service addresses a specific pain — must map 1:1 to pains in the Customer Profile</item>
          <item>Gain Creators: how each product/service enables a specific gain — must map 1:1 to gains in the Customer Profile</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="fit-assessment">
        <rule>
          <statement>FIT is achieved when Pain Relievers address the top-ranked pains and Gain Creators enable the essential gains. Focus on pains rated 8+ and gains labeled "essential" or "expected" — ignore "nice to have."</statement>
          <rationale>Building against low-intensity pains and desired-but-not-essential gains produces features customers acknowledge but do not pay for.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="canvas-decay-rule">
        <rule>
          <statement>Add a valid_until date (90 days from creation) to every VPC. Expire and force regeneration in CI when the date passes.</statement>
          <rationale>VPC pains and gains shift quarterly in early markets. A 6-month-old canvas built on unvalidated assumptions guides product decisions in the wrong direction.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="pricing-model-selection">
      <section name="six-pricing-models">
        <list>
          <item>Freemium: free tier + paid upgrade; best for high-volume, low-marginal-cost products; typical conversion 2-5% system-wide (not "qualified users")</item>
          <item>Subscription: recurring payment for ongoing value; predictable revenue; churn risk requires LTV/CAC above 3:1</item>
          <item>Usage-based: pay for consumption; scales with customer value delivered; revenue unpredictability is the primary risk</item>
          <item>One-time purchase: single payment for perpetual access; simple but no recurring revenue; suits discrete value or impulse buys</item>
          <item>Tiered: different feature levels at different prices; captures more value across segments; requires 3 distinct WTP segments with different jobs-to-be-done to justify</item>
          <item>Per-seat: per-user pricing; clear and predictable; creates resistance to adding users in small teams</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="model-selection-rules">
        <rule>
          <statement>Default-reject "tiered subscription" and force the agent to argue for it. Reject unless 3 distinct WTP segments with different jobs-to-be-done can be named.</statement>
          <rationale>"Tiered subscription" is the default LLM answer for any SaaS regardless of actual economics. Requiring explicit justification defeats this bias and forces evaluation of usage-based and hybrid models that often dominate real economics.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>For pricing research, never use LLM-simulated willingness-to-pay surveys. Use Van Westendorp with real respondents via a survey tool (Conjointly, Pollfish, Qualtrics).</statement>
          <rationale>LLM-simulated WTP surveys produce regression-to-mean prices ($19/$49/$99) regardless of niche. Synthetic respondents cannot replicate actual buyer psychology or budget constraints.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="pricing-research-process">
        <list>
          <item>Step 1: list top 5 competitors' pricing models, tiers, and price ranges (from competitor-analysis output)</item>
          <item>Step 2: calculate value delivered (cost of problem eliminated, time saved in hours per month)</item>
          <item>Step 3: apply Van Westendorp PSM with real respondents — 4 price-sensitivity questions, minimum n=50</item>
          <item>Step 4: test with early users before publishing tiers</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="llm-bias-mitigations">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Agent recommends "tiered subscription" without naming 3 distinct WTP segments</description>
          <reason>Forces the agent to reason about actual buyer segments and job differences rather than defaulting to the industry template.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>WTP estimates anchored to $19/$49/$99 with no external benchmark</description>
          <reason>Pin to a ProfitWell category report or competitor scrape before letting the agent suggest tiers. Without a benchmark, LLMs regress to round numbers.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/niche-scorecard.md" purpose="Weighted niche viability scorecard with justification and decision columns"/>
      <template path="templates/blue-ocean-canvas.md" purpose="Blue Ocean Four Actions canvas template"/>
      <template path="templates/value-proposition-canvas.md" purpose="VPC template with customer profile and value map sections"/>
      <template path="templates/pricing-strategy.md" purpose="Pricing strategy document with competitor table and tier definitions"/>
      <template path="templates/score-niche.sh" purpose="Bash/jq script that validates weights sum to 1.0 and recomputes weighted total from a JSON sidecar"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
